3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Funding rates on Bluefin are calculated hourly using a time-weighted average of the premium between perpetual price and spot index. The exchange uses Pyth Network oracles for real-time price feeds, with funding payments automatically debited/credited to trader positions at each hour. Bluefin's on-chain settlement means funding transactions are immediately final without traditional exchange custody risks. The 0.02% maker / 0.05% taker fee structure influences net funding profitability calculations."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","UNI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"UNI perpetuals on Bluefin often exhibit higher funding rate volatility due to the platform's concentrated Sui ecosystem liquidity and UNI's role as a major DeFi governance token. The hourly funding frequency creates more granular arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour systems, potentially benefiting active traders who can capture shorter-term rate fluctuations."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"UNI/USDT funding rates on Bluefin typically range from -0.05% to +0.15% hourly, with higher volatility during DeFi market events or Uniswap governance proposals. The Sui ecosystem's early stage means lower overall volume can create pronounced funding rate spikes when directional positioning becomes crowded. Patterns show increased negative funding during broader crypto selloffs when UNI shorts dominate, while DeFi rallies often push rates significantly positive. The hourly reset cycle creates more frequent mean reversion opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour funding models."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Platform Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Funding rate disparities between Bluefin and major CEXs like Binance or OKX can exceed 0.1% hourly during volatile periods, creating profitable arbitrage setups. Bluefin's Sui-based settlement allows rapid position adjustments without CEX withdrawal delays, though arbitrageurs must account for bridge timing when moving USDT between ecosystems. The platform's lower liquidity means funding rates can deviate more dramatically from larger venues, particularly during Asian trading hours when Sui activity peaks. Cross-DEX arbitrage opportunities also exist with other Sui perpetual platforms, though volume constraints limit position sizing."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Limitations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bluefin's early-stage ecosystem presents unique risks including lower liquidity depth that can cause significant slippage on larger positions during funding arbitrage execution. Sui blockchain congestion, while rare, could affect funding payment timing and arbitrage precision. The platform's concentrated user base means funding rates may not always reflect broader market sentiment, creating basis risk for arbitrageurs. Smart contract risk exists with any DEX, though Bluefin has undergone professional audits, and the Sui runtime provides additional safety through its object-centric architecture."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Bluefin's hourly funding compare to 8-hour cycles on other exchanges?","answer":"Bluefin's hourly funding creates 8x more arbitrage opportunities but requires more active monitoring. The shorter cycles mean funding rates tend to mean-revert faster, reducing the duration risk of arbitrage positions but potentially lowering per-trade profitability."},{"question":"What are the gas costs for funding arbitrage on Sui compared to other chains?","answer":"Sui transactions typically cost under $0.01, making frequent position adjustments economically viable for funding arbitrage strategies. The low gas costs allow profitable arbitrage on smaller position sizes compared to Ethereum-based DEXs where gas can exceed funding rate profits."},{"question":"How does UNI liquidity on Bluefin affect funding rate arbitrage execution?","answer":"UNI/USDT typically maintains $100K-500K in order book depth on Bluefin, sufficient for most retail arbitrage strategies but potentially limiting for institutional-size positions. The concentrated liquidity means arbitrageurs should use limit orders to avoid market impact that could erode funding rate advantages."},{"question":"Can funding rate arbitrage be automated on Bluefin using APIs?","answer":"Bluefin provides REST and WebSocket APIs that support automated trading strategies including funding rate monitoring and execution. The on-chain nature means all trades are transparent and verifiable, though API rate limits may constrain high-frequency funding arbitrage approaches."}]}]
